TinyStories/training/sampler jobs. Success criterion: either fresh passing preflight artifacts that justify retrying the infrastructure gate, or updated state/report artifacts identifying a precise unrecoverable operator-side blocker and the minimal operator action needed.\",\"time_budget_hours\":0.5,\"expected_cost_usd\":0,\"rationale\":\"AGENTS.md requires the infrastructure gate before pilot/final work, and the executive plan makes this the first decisive gate. The last executor decision was blocked, so the sequencing rules call for a diagnose-and-fix tick rather than retrying the same infrastructure gate unchanged. This bounded zero-cost action may recover an environment activation issue or sharpen the CUDA/device-node diagnosis while preserving the remaining 7.9 hours and staying within the hard budget.\"}results/_codex/planner-003/final_decision.json\n{\"terminal_decision\":\"escalate\",\"stage\":\"diagnose_and_fix\",\"executor_prompt\":\"codex/prompts/diagnose_and_fix.md\",\"task_instruction\":\"Halt for operator-side CUDA driver repair before any further experiment work. Required recovery: stop/start or reboot the VM from the operator side, rerun the official Google GPU driver installer if needed, verify `nvidia-smi` succeeds and PyTorch sees the L4, then resume with the infrastructure gate only.\",\"time_budget_hours\":0,\"expected_cost_usd\":0,\"rationale\":\"The infrastructure gate is blocked by a deterministic worker-visible driver failure: CUDA-enabled PyTorch is installed, the L4 is visible on PCI, and NVIDIA kernel modules are loaded, but `nvidia-smi` cannot communicate with the driver and PyTorch sees zero CUDA devices. The worker cannot perform cloud lifecycle or driver repair actions under AGENTS.md, and retrying pilot/final/LLC work would violate the gate order. This is not a spend approval issue; it is an external operator repair requirement.\"}","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
